Aviation Fatigue Risk Management System (FRMS) Simulator 
Project Overview
This project is a high-fidelity Fatigue Risk Management System (FRMS) Simulator designed to analyze pilot fatigue and operational risks in large-scale airline rosters. By simulating 10,000+ flight duty periods, the system identifies "Red Zones" where fatigue levels exceed safety thresholds based on international aviation regulations and human circadian biology.

Key Features
Large-Scale Simulation: Generates and analyzes 10,000+ synthetic flight rosters to mimic real-world airline operations.
Regulatory Compliance: Integrated EASA FTL (Flight Time Limitations) logic to flag duties exceeding 13 hours.
Circadian Biology Integration: Features a WOCL (Window of Circadian Low) scoring engine that penalizes duties starting between 02:00 and 06:00.
Predictive Risk Scoring: Dynamically calculates fatigue scores for every duty period, identifying critical "Red Zones" for proactive intervention.

Core Methodology & Logic

The simulator evaluates risk using a multi-factor weighted algorithm:
Fatigue\_Score = (Duty\_Length \times 5) + (WOCL\_Penalty) + (Regulatory\_Violation)

Base Fatigue Score: Calculated as a function of Duty Length (5 points per hour).
Circadian Penalty (WOCL): Duties overlapping the 02:00 - 06:00 window (Window of Circadian Low) receive a +30 risk weight due to heightened physiological vulnerability.
Regulatory Cap: Any duty exceeding 13 hours (per EASA FTL guidelines) triggers an immediate +50 safety violation penalty.

Results & Analytics:
Total Rosters Analyzed: 10,000.
Red Zone Alerts Detected: 743 (7.43%).
Analysis: The most severe risks were identified in long-haul duties starting during the WOCL window, demonstrating the model's high sensitivity to physiological and regulatory risks.


